{"title_page": "FC Slutsk", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Slutsk\n| image      = Fc-slutsk-logo.png\n| fullname   = Athletic Football Club Slutsk<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|url=http://sfc-slutsk.by/About|website=Sfc-slutsk.by|publisher=\u0421\u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n| nickname   = \n| shortname  = \n| founded    = 1998\n| dissolved  = \n| ground     = [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|City Stadium]], [[Slutsk]]\n| capacity   = 1,896\n| chrtitle   = Chairman\n| chairman   = Oleg Karanevsky\n| mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n| manager    = [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]]\n| league     = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season     = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position   = 11th\n| website    = http://sfc-slutsk.by\n| pattern_la1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_b1  = _eastern18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so1 = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = 0000FF\n| body1       = 0000FF\n| rightarm1   = 0000FF\n| shorts1     = 0000FF\n| socks1      = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _unterhaching1819t\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Slutsk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}) is a [[Belarus]]ian football club based in [[Slutsk]], [[Minsk Oblast]].\n\n==History==\nThere was competitive soccer in [[Slutsk]] as early as 1913,<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\">{{cite web | title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0430 | website=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f | url=http://nasledie-sluck.by/ru/sluchina/History_organizations/5151/ | language=ru | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> with a Slutsk team entering the third season of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|republican]] competition in 1926, but it did not enter a BSSR competition again until 1936.  From the 1940s, the city of Slutsk was represented at a very low level by a team called Slutsk Spartak.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\">{{cite web | title=Centennial Timeline of Slutsk Football \u2022 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | website=\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | date=April 10, 2020 | url=https://kurjer.info/2020/04/10/100-football-english-version/ | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> During World War 2, the city's soccer ground was the site of \"fierce battles\" and extensive trench construction. In 1948 the city's executive committee decided to promote and fund soccer. The same year, the [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|city stadium]], originally built 1935, was rebuilt. In addition to government funding, the city team was funded by the \"trade union voluntary sports society and individual enterprises.\" Despite this, by 1974 the Slutsk team faced financial difficulties and dropped out of the BSSR republican championship. There were short-lived revivals in 1980 and the late 1980s, before the city registered a self-supporting club in 1990. The name of the Slutsk team changed frequently in the 1990s, based on sponsorship.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/>\n\nIn 1997, there was a new sports center in Slutsk funded by Nikolai Prudnik, of the local sugar refinery. The sports complex created a soccer team funded by Oleg Karanevsky, a [[physical education|physical educator]]. It was initially effectively a company team for the sugar plant, with all the players working for the plant, but later players from previous Slutsk representative teams joined. The coach was Alexander Dubitsky.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/>\n\nThe current team was founded in 1998 as '''Slutsksakhar Slutsk''' after success in local [[futsal]] and financial guarantees from the sugar refinery.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/> Between 1998 and 2007 they played in the Minsk Oblast championship. In 2008, they joined the [[Belarusian Second League]]. In 2010, they finished in second place and were granted a promotion to the [[Belarusian First League|First League]] in 2011. In early 2011 the team changed its name to '''Slutsk'''. After becoming a \"city club\", initially all home matches were played at a stadium in [[Salihorsk]].<ref name=\"Regiony.BY\">{{cite web | title=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438 :: \u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 | website=Regiony.BY | url=https://horki.regiony.by/#!news/1398 | language=ru | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> Starting in 2012, after expansion of the [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|Slutsk city stadium]], with a new administrative building, new stands, and a pitch extension, the team began playing at their proper home ground. The pitch had initially been too small, as a running track around the field had been only 360 meters instead of the standard 400.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/> In 2013, Slutsk became the league leader in home attendance.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\"/> The town stadium would be further renovated in the 2014 season.\n\nIn 2014, the club hired Japanese player [[Y\u014dsuke Sait\u014d]], who would score 7 goals in 17 games in his debut season.\n\nIn the 2015 off-season Slutsk was one of the few Belarusian teams to play friendlies abroad, facing Danish and Russian clubs in Turkey.\n\nIn the following seasons, the club went through a series of management changes. In 2015, long-time head coach [[Yuriy Krot]] was fired, replaced by [[Vyacheslav Grigorov]], who was also a player. In 2017, [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]] was appointed head coach. The same year Oleg Karanevsky, club chairman, was detained for allegedly taking a bribe.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2017\">{{cite web | title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0421\u0424\u041a \u00ab\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u00bb \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0438. \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e, \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u2022 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | website=\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | date=September 7, 2017 | url=https://kurjer.info/2017/09/07/sfk/ | language=ky | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, forward [[Yevgeniy Shikavka]] was the first FC Slutsk player to represent Belarus at the national level.\n\nIn 2020 the club suffered a financial setback when the major sponsor, a local sugar refinery, withdrew after suffering losses.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\"/> The decision was made by new management, since the former head was imprisoned.<ref name = \"Lusted 2020-video\">Lusted, Peter, \"[https://vimeo.com/411698581 Saving Slustk]\", ''ABC News Australia'', aired April 25, 2020.</ref>\n\nFC Slutsk gained global media attention during the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]. As the Belarusian league was one of the few in the world still playing (along with Nicaragua and Tajikistan), an online following began around FC Slutsk, started by Australians who found the name funny.<ref name=\"\u00ab\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u0412\u00bb \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d 2020\">{{cite web | title=FC Slutsk finds unexpected fame with 1,500 fans worldwide | website=\u00ab\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u0412\u00bb \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d | date=March 22, 2020 | url=https://belsat.eu/en/news/fc-slutsk-finds-unexpected-fame-with-1-300-fans-worldwide/ | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Today 2020\">{{cite web | last=Today | first=Russia | title=The story of FK Slutsk, football's unlikely Belarusian heroes | website=RT International | date=March 31, 2020 | url=https://www.rt.com/sport/484586-belarus-football-fk-slutsk-coronavirus/ | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Sport 2020\">{{cite web | title=Belarus football's new global following as Belarusian Premier League continues unabated | website=BBC Sport | date=April 2, 2020 | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/52122767 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Dunne 2020\">{{cite web | last=Dunne | first=Jessica | title=What Sports Are Still Being Played Around The World? | website=10 daily | date=April 5, 2020 | url=https://10daily.com.au/news/sport/a200405cvrlj/what-sports-are-still-being-played-around-the-world-20200405 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>\"[https://www.facebook.com/DatelineSBS/posts/10163141358075411 Belarus' Global League: Sport during the coronavirus era]\", ''SBS Dateline'', April 24, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"NBC News 2020\">{{cite web | title=In Belarus, unlike most places, soccer plays on despite virus | website=NBC News | date=April 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/belarus-unlike-most-places-soccer-plays-despite-virus-n1187701 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Post 2020\">{{cite web | last=Post | first=South China Morning | title=Coronavirus: football stands firm in Belarus, Tajikistan, Burundi, Nicaragua | website=LINE TODAY | date=April 7, 2020 | url=https://today.line.me/hk/article/Coronavirus+football+stands+firm+in+Belarus+Tajikistan+Burundi+Nicaragua-m60Vlz | language=en | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref> This led to coverage of the club by international media outlets including the [[BBC]], the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], [[Russia Today]], and the [[Sueddeutsche Zeitung]]. The new fandom also had financial benefits: when the club's financial problems came to light, online fans raised \"over $3,000 in less than two weeks\" to help the club, and led to new sponsorship from a Ukraininan betting company.<ref name=\"Lusted 2020\">{{cite web | last=Lusted | first=Peter | title=How Australians in shutdown suddenly became a Belarusian soccer club's number one fans | website=ABC News | date=April 24, 2020 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-24/aussie-sports-fans-help-belarus-football-club-during-coronavirus/12178348 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gofundme.com\">''Fundraiser by Shane Robinson : FK Slutsk Worldwide Official Donation Fund'', Apr 24, 2020.</ref> The movement also led to the adoption of a club song, \"We love our Slutsk\", composed by Andy Bajana,<ref>Trubila, Yury, \"FK SLUTSK WORLDWIDE ANTHEM - WE LOVE OUR SLUTSK (\u0413\u0438\u043c\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a)\", YouTube, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o91axfV3yiY.</ref> which was played at home games starting in April 2020.<ref name=\"Reich 2020\">{{cite web | last=Reich | first=Stephan | title=Fleisch p\u00f6keln, Tampons verzieren | website=SZ Magazin | date=April 24, 2020 | url=https://sz-magazin.sueddeutsche.de/leben-und-gesellschaft/corona-hobby-88730 | language=de | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"Lusted 2020-video\"/>\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of March 2020 ''<ref>[http://sfc-slutsk.by/club/teams/main FC Slutsk squad]</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Vitali Trubila]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Yuriy Teterenko]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|name=[[Yegor Semenov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=9|name=[[Artyom Serdyuk]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|name=[[Soslan Takulov]]|nat=RUS|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|name=[[Vladislav Sychev]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|name=[[Pavel Zuyevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|name=[[Umar Bala Mohammed]]|nat=NGA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|name=[[Souleymane Koanda]]|nat=BFA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|name=[[Dzyanis Obrazaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|name=[[Yevgeniy Velko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|name=[[Igor Bobko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|name=[[Yury Kazlow]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|name=[[Serhiy Chebotayev]]|nat=UKR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|name=[[Ilya Branovets]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|name=[[Barys Pankrataw]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=55|name=[[Alyaksandr Anyukevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=59|name=[[Roman Krivulkin]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=71|name=[[Marat Burayev]]|nat=RUS|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=77|name=[[Alan Koroyev]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=78|name=[[Abdoul Gafar Sirima]]|nat=BFA|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=99|name=[[Dramane Salou]]|nat=BFA|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==League and Cup history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=55|Season\n!width=50|{{Tooltip|Level|League level}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pos|Position}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=60|Goals\n!width=45|Points\n![[Belarusian Cup|Domestic Cup]]\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2008 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''5''' || 30 || 15 || 6 || 9 || 53\u201337 || '''51''' || || \n|-\n| 2009 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''4''' || 26 || 14 || 3 || 9 || 48\u201337 || '''45''' ||Round of 64 || \n|-\n| 2010 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''2''' || 34 || 25 || 6 || 3 || 79\u201330 || '''81''' ||Round of 32 || Promoted\n|-\n| 2011 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''5''' || 30 || 13 || 10 || 7 || 44\u201333 || '''49''' ||Round of 32  || \n|-\n| 2012 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''5''' || 28 || 15 || 7 || 6 || 59\u201327 || '''52''' ||Round of 32  ||\n|-\n| 2013 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''1''' || 30 || 19 || 9 || 2 || 54\u201319 || '''66''' ||Round of 32  || Promoted\n|-\n| 2014 || 1st || '''9''' || 32 || 11 || 7 || 14 || 26\u201334 || '''40''' ||Round of 16  ||\n|-\n| 2015 || 1st || '''11''' || 26 || 6 || 7 || 13 || 26-30 || '''25''' ||Round of 16  ||\n|-\n| 2016 || 1st || '''12''' || 30 || 6 || 12 || 12 || 22-34 || '''30''' || Quarter-finals ||\n|-\n| 2017 || 1st || '''8''' || 30 || 12 || 8 || 10 || 30-34 || '''44''' || Quarter-finals ||\n|-\n| 2018 || 1st || '''8''' || 30 || 11 || 3 || 16 || 26-36 || '''36''' || Quarter-finals ||\n|-\n| 2019 || 1st || '''11''' || 30 || 9 || 7 || 14 || 29-46 || '''34''' || Quarter-finals ||\n|-\n| 2020 || 1st || '''5''' || 4 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 7-5 || '''7''' || Round of 16 ||\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n*Champions - [[Belarusian First League]] - 2013\n**Runners-Up - [[Belarusian Second League]] - 2010\n\n==Managers==\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Yuriy Krot]] (2005\u201315)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vyachaslaw Hryharaw]] (2015\u20132016)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]] (2017\u2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sfc-slutsk.by/  Official Website] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{Belarusian Premier League teamlist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slutsk}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Sport in Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Slutsk\n| image      = Fc-slutsk-logo.png\n| fullname   = Athletic Football Club Slutsk<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|url=http://sfc-slutsk.by/About|website=Sfc-slutsk.by|publisher=\u0421\u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n| nickname   = \n| shortname  = \n| founded    = 1998\n| dissolved  = \n| ground     = [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|City Stadium]], [[Slutsk]]\n| capacity   = 1,896\n| chrtitle   = Chairman\n| chairman   = Oleg Karanevsky\n| mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n| manager    = [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]]\n| league     = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season     = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position   = 11th\n| website    = http://sfc-slutsk.by\n| pattern_la1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_b1  = _eastern18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so1 = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = 0000FF\n| body1       = 0000FF\n| rightarm1   = 0000FF\n| shorts1     = 0000FF\n| socks1      = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _unterhaching1819t\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Slutsk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}) is a [[Belarus]]ian football club based in [[Slutsk]], [[Minsk Oblast]].\n\n==History==\nThere was competitive soccer in [[Slutsk]] as early as 1913,<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\">{{cite web | title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0430 | website=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f | url=http://nasledie-sluck.by/ru/sluchina/History_organizations/5151/ | language=ru | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> with a Slutsk team entering the third season of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|republican]] competition in 1926, but it did not enter a BSSR competition again until 1936.  From the 1940s, the city of Slutsk was represented at a very low level by a team called Slutsk Spartak.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\">{{cite web | title=Centennial Timeline of Slutsk Football \u2022 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | website=\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | date=April 10, 2020 | url=https://kurjer.info/2020/04/10/100-football-english-version/ | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> During World War 2, the city's soccer ground was the site of \"fierce battles\" and extensive trench construction. In 1948 the city's executive committee decided to promote and fund soccer. The same year, the [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|city stadium]], originally built 1935, was rebuilt. In addition to government funding, the city team was funded by the \"trade union voluntary sports society and individual enterprises.\" Despite this, by 1974 the Slutsk team faced financial difficulties and dropped out of the BSSR republican championship. There were short-lived revivals in 1980 and the late 1980s, before a the city registered a self-supporting club in 1990. The name of the Slutsk team changed frequently in the 1990s, based on sponsorship.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/>\n\nIn 1997, there was a new sports center in Slutsk funded by Nikolai Prudnik, of the local sugar refinery. The sports complex created a soccer team funded by Oleg Karanevsky, a [[physical education|physical educator]]. It was initially effectively a company team for the sugar plant, with all the players working for the plant, but later players from previous Slutsk representative teams joined. The coach was Alexander Dubitsky.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/>\n\nThe current team was founded in 1998 as '''Slutsksakhar Slutsk''' after success in local [[futsal]] and financial guarantees from the sugar refinery.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/> Between 1998 and 2007 they played in the Minsk Oblast championship. In 2008, they joined the [[Belarusian Second League]]. In 2010, they finished in second place and were granted a promotion to the [[Belarusian First League|First League]] in 2011. In early 2011 the team changed its name to '''Slutsk'''. After becoming a \"city club\", initially all home matches were played at a stadium in [[Salihorsk]].<ref name=\"Regiony.BY\">{{cite web | title=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438 :: \u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 | website=Regiony.BY | url=https://horki.regiony.by/#!news/1398 | language=ru | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref> Starting in 2012, after expansion of the [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|Slutsk city stadium]], with a new administrative building, new stands, and a pitch extension, the team began playing at their proper home ground. The pitch had initially been too small, as a running track around the field had been only 360 meters instead of the standard 400.<ref name=\"\u041d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f\"/> In 2013, Slutsk became the league leader in home attendance.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\"/> The town stadium would be further renovated in the 2014 season.\n\nIn 2014, the club hired Japanese player [[Y\u014dsuke Sait\u014d]], who would score 7 goals in 17 games in his debut season.\n\nIn the 2015 off-season Slutsk was one of the few Belarusian teams to play friendlies abroad, facing Danish and Russian clubs in Turkey.\n\nIn the following seasons, the club went through a series of management changes. In 2015, long-time head coach [[Yuriy Krot]] was fired, replaced by [[Vyacheslav Grigorov]], who was also a player. In 2017, [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]] was appointed head coach. The same year Oleg Karanevsky, club chairman, was detained for allegedly taking a bribe.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2017\">{{cite web | title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0421\u0424\u041a \u00ab\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u00bb \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0438. \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e, \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u2022 \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | website=\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb | date=September 7, 2017 | url=https://kurjer.info/2017/09/07/sfk/ | language=ky | access-date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, forward [[Yevgeniy Shikavka]] was the first FC Slutsk player to represent Belarus at the national level.\n\nIn 2020 the club suffered a financial setback when the major sponsor, a local sugar refinery, withdrew after suffering losses.<ref name=\"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a \u2022 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u0406\u043d\u0444\u0430-\u041a\u0443\u0440\u2019\u0435\u0440\u00bb 2020\"/> The decision was made by new management, since the former head was imprisoned.<ref name = \"Lusted 2020-video\">Lusted, Peter, \"[https://vimeo.com/411698581 Saving Slustk]\", ''ABC News Australia'', aired April 25, 2020.</ref>\n\nFC Slutsk gained global media attention during the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]. As the Belarusian league was one of the few in the world still playing (along with Nicaragua and Tajikistan), an online following began around FC Slutsk, started by Australians who found the name funny.<ref name=\"\u00ab\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u0412\u00bb \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d 2020\">{{cite web | title=FC Slutsk finds unexpected fame with 1,500 fans worldwide | website=\u00ab\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u0412\u00bb \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d | date=March 22, 2020 | url=https://belsat.eu/en/news/fc-slutsk-finds-unexpected-fame-with-1-300-fans-worldwide/ | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Today 2020\">{{cite web | last=Today | first=Russia | title=The story of FK Slutsk, football's unlikely Belarusian heroes | website=RT International | date=March 31, 2020 | url=https://www.rt.com/sport/484586-belarus-football-fk-slutsk-coronavirus/ | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Sport 2020\">{{cite web | title=Belarus football's new global following as Belarusian Premier League continues unabated | website=BBC Sport | date=April 2, 2020 | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/52122767 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Dunne 2020\">{{cite web | last=Dunne | first=Jessica | title=What Sports Are Still Being Played Around The World? | website=10 daily | date=April 5, 2020 | url=https://10daily.com.au/news/sport/a200405cvrlj/what-sports-are-still-being-played-around-the-world-20200405 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>\"[https://www.facebook.com/DatelineSBS/posts/10163141358075411 Belarus' Global League: Sport during the coronavirus era]\", ''SBS Dateline'', April 24, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"NBC News 2020\">{{cite web | title=In Belarus, unlike most places, soccer plays on despite virus | website=NBC News | date=April 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/belarus-unlike-most-places-soccer-plays-despite-virus-n1187701 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Post 2020\">{{cite web | last=Post | first=South China Morning | title=Coronavirus: football stands firm in Belarus, Tajikistan, Burundi, Nicaragua | website=LINE TODAY | date=April 7, 2020 | url=https://today.line.me/hk/article/Coronavirus+football+stands+firm+in+Belarus+Tajikistan+Burundi+Nicaragua-m60Vlz | language=en | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref> This led to coverage of the club by international media outlets including the [[BBC]], the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], [[Russia Today]], and the [[Sueddeutsche Zeitung]]. The new fandom also had financial benefits: when the club's financial problems came to light, online fans raised \"over $3,000 in less than two weeks\" to help the club, and led to new sponsorship from a Ukraininan betting company.<ref name=\"Lusted 2020\">{{cite web | last=Lusted | first=Peter | title=How Australians in shutdown suddenly became a Belarusian soccer club's number one fans | website=ABC News | date=April 24, 2020 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-24/aussie-sports-fans-help-belarus-football-club-during-coronavirus/12178348 | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gofundme.com\">''Fundraiser by Shane Robinson : FK Slutsk Worldwide Official Donation Fund'', Apr 24, 2020.</ref> The movement also led to the adoption of a club song, \"We love our Slutsk\", composed by Andy Bajana,<ref>Trubila, Yury, \"FK SLUTSK WORLDWIDE ANTHEM - WE LOVE OUR SLUTSK (\u0413\u0438\u043c\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a)\", YouTube, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o91axfV3yiY.</ref> which was played at home games starting in April 2020.<ref name=\"Reich 2020\">{{cite web | last=Reich | first=Stephan | title=Fleisch p\u00f6keln, Tampons verzieren | website=SZ Magazin | date=April 24, 2020 | url=https://sz-magazin.sueddeutsche.de/leben-und-gesellschaft/corona-hobby-88730 | language=de | access-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"Lusted 2020-video\"/>\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of March 2020 ''<ref>[http://sfc-slutsk.by/club/teams/main FC Slutsk squad]</ref>\n\n{{